TICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
1. For dual-weilding, you'll tend to want a faster weapon in the main hand to take advantage of the damage bonus, which increases as you level up.  The best weapons for under level 33 are purely determined by damage:delay ratio, since there is no damage bonus.  The best weapon for the off-hand is always determined by damage:delay ratio.  Lower delay is better for taunt -- tends to keep a critter's attention.  Longer delay is better for avoiding riposte and damage shield damage.<br>
<br>
There's no hard and fast rule on main hand for what weapon is best.  There are a number of calculations you can try that provide a rough comparison (see steel warrior or monkly-business web sites for those).  In general, faster will provide better taunt, better DPS (in main hand at high level), and more skill ups.<br>
<br>
Once you get 60+, you'll start to find that 2H weapons can provide nearly as much taunt and that they also significantly reduce riposte damage.  This is for warriors and monks only btw -- only they get tripple attack and have a choice to dual or not.  When you fight creatures that hit for 300 on up to 900, you can see that reducing riposte damage can have a major impact on how much damage you take as a tank.<br>
<br>
2. There is no such thing as &quot;damage type&quot; in EQ.  It doesn't matter if it comes from a piercer or a club, melee damage is all the same.  The only reason you want to work on all of your skills is so you don't have to play catch-up on them to use a nice weapon you manage to acquire outside your specialty.  My dumb ogre warrior was able to max out every single weapon skill every level.  It's really not hard to do once you acquire some fast weapons (faster == more swings == more chances to skill up).<br>
<br>
3. Enrage happens when a critter gets down to where it would normally death-crawl if it didn't enrage.  What it means is that while enraged, the critter will automatically riposte on every single attack.  This is when at least everyone from the front needs to turn off attack or they'll quickly die (think 300-900 per hit with dual wield delivering up to 5 attacks per round).  Back row might turn off, too, to avoid a flip.<br>
<br>
Rogues often accidently flip the critter when they get a really nice backstab.  This is bad for the rogue, since he's now tanking a heavy hitter.  It's bad for the raid, since the back row is now open to ripostes.  If this is during enrage and back row is still active, said rogue can kill off the entire back row.  I always turn off attack during enrage, back or front.<br>
<br>
The other time everyone will keep attack turned off is so that the MT can build up an agro-lead that won't result in flips and more dead in the back row.  Typically this is only during the start of a fight, but you might also see it during MT transitions when the main MT dies or /defensive runs out.  Fights that rely on /defensive transitioning are typcaily some of the hardest in the game.  Moving agro from one MT to another without bouncing the critter around amongs the back row is not easy even when people do turn off attack.  It's nearly impossible when they don't turn it off.  Why don't they?  'Cuz they're lagged out so bad they don't know they're even being hit or that the MT died.  This is why heavy raiding guilds often have a &quot;cable modem required&quot; clause.  If you lag, not only do you die, but you can wipe the raid.<br>
<br>
Flurry is another trick some high level critters have.  Basically, it's a free set of about 2-6 blows from a critter that happens pretty much identically to a proc or a crit.  Crippling a critter will reduce flurries and procs.  What this does is cause the clerics to use a shorter CH interval than might be required just to account for potential flurries.  Either that, or you run a spam-heal group where several healers will all pop quick-heals onto the MT after every flurry.<br>
<br>
Vellious rampage is is pretty much an AE melee attack to the top of the agro list.  Luclin rampage is a seperate agro list entirely and once you get on it, almost nothing can get you off of it (not even camping out and back).  FD will prevent rampage from hitting you, but when you stand up, you'll be back on it again.  Fortunately, the rampage list is short.  How folks deal with this is they orchestrate the agro so that only those that can handle it best are on the rampage list.  They will typically have several CH'ers watching out for them and healing the rampage damage.  This is what people mean by &quot;rampage tank&quot; as opposed to &quot;main tank&quot;.  The fact that a couple end-game guilds were using monks for rampage tanks was supposedly the root cause of the monk nerf.<br>
<br>
